msgstr "Renault FT"

msgid "F01_RenaultFT_descr"
msgstr ""
"The vehicle entered service in 1917, with 3,177 vehicles manufactured by the "
"end of World War I and 3,800 vehicles produced in total. At the beginning of "
"World War II, a total of 1,560 vehicles were in service."

msgid "F01_RenaultFT_short"
msgstr "FT"

msgid "F04_B1"
msgstr "B1"

msgid "F04_B1_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development was started in 1921. The vehicle entered service in 1934. A "
"total of 403 tanks were manufactured at Renault, FCM, Schneider, FAHM, and "
"AMX factories. The vehicle was upgraded numerous times. Despite the outdated "
"configuration, this tank earned a reputation as an invincible vehicle with "
"reliable armor in battles against German troops from May through June 1940."

msgid "F04_B1_short"
msgstr "B1"

msgid "F05_BDR_G1B"
msgstr "BDR G1 B"

msgid "F05_BDR_G1B_descr"
msgstr ""
"The project of a new vehicle was suggested by engineers of the Baudet-Donon-"
"Roussel company in June 1938, but the design was never developed."

msgid "F05_BDR_G1B_short"
msgstr "BDR G1 B"

msgid "F06_ARL_44"
msgstr "ARL 44"

msgid "F06_ARL_44_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development of the vehicle started while France was still occupied by the "
"German forces. It was an attempt to use the obsolete B1 Bis chassis and fit "
"it with a modern, more powerful gun. The project was finished by the Atelier "
"de Construction de Rueil Design Bureau. A total of 60 vehicles were "
"manufactured. However, the tank was considered unsuccessful compared to "
"similar foreign vehicles."

msgid "F06_ARL_44_short"
msgstr "ARL 44"

msgid "F07_AMX_M4_1945"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 45"

msgid "F07_AMX_M4_1945_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development of this heavy tank started in 1945. The vehicle incorporated "
"several design features of the Pz.Kpfw. VI Ausf. B Tiger II tank. The "
"vehicle existed only in blueprints. Later the AMX M4 (1945) became a "
"prototype for the AMX 50 100."

msgid "F07_AMX_M4_1945_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 45"

msgid "F08_AMX_50_100"
msgstr "AMX 50 100"

msgid "F08_AMX_50_100_descr"
msgstr ""
"The AMX 50 100 heavy tank was a further development of the M4 project. The "
"first prototype was built in 1949. The 55-ton vehicle featured a 100-mm gun "
"in the oscillating turret. The prototype was tested with gasoline and diesel "
"engines from 1950 through 1952. The vehicle never entered mass production "
"nor saw service."

msgid "F08_AMX_50_100_short"
msgstr "AMX 50 100"

msgid "F09_AMX_50_120"
msgstr "AMX 50 120"

msgid "F09_AMX_50_120_descr"
msgstr ""
"A prototype of the AMX 50 tank. Developed in the early 1950s under the "
"influence of the Soviet IS-3 and T-10. The tank featured enhanced armor and "
"a 120-mm gun in the oscillating turret."

msgid "F09_AMX_50_120_short"
msgstr "AMX 50 120"

msgid "F100_Panhard_EBR_90"
msgstr "Panhard EBR 90"

msgid "F100_Panhard_EBR_90_descr"
msgstr ""
"In the early 1960s, the 75 mm caliber guns were deemed outdated. During 1963 "
"and 1964, a total of 650 vehicles with FL 11 turrets were re-equipped with "
"90 mm guns to improve their firepower. The other vehicles with the same "
"turret and \"outdated\" guns were removed from service in the French Army."

msgid "F100_Panhard_EBR_90_short"
msgstr "EBR 90"

msgid "F106_Panhard_EBR_75_Mle1954"
msgstr "Panhard EBR 75 (FL 10)"

msgid "F106_Panhard_EBR_75_Mle1954_descr"
msgstr ""
"Between 1954 and 1955, a number of Panhard EBR armored vehicles were "
"equipped with the AMX 13 75 FL 10 turrets to improve their firepower. They "
"had the same turret rings and no changes were required in terms of the hull "
"design. The modernized armored vehicles were deployed with the French Army."

msgid "F106_Panhard_EBR_75_Mle1954_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A wheeled vehicle with four axles and two movement modes: Cruise and Rapid. "
"Its mediocre view range and low firepower are compensated for by fantastic "
"speed and dynamics. In addition, good concealment puts this vehicle in the "
"role of an active scout and makes it effective for flanking maneuvers and "
"breaking through enemy lines."

msgid "F106_Panhard_EBR_75_Mle1954_short"
msgstr "EBR 75 FL 10"

msgid "F106_Panhard_EBR_75_Mle1954_short_special"
msgstr "Fantastic speed and dynamics, good stabilization and concealment"

msgid "F107_Hotchkiss_EBR"
msgstr "Hotchkiss EBR"

msgid "F107_Hotchkiss_EBR_descr"
msgstr ""
"The development of this armored vehicle was part of the corresponding "
"program approved by the military leaders in 1945. In 1949, the Hotchkiss "
"company presented a three-axis prototype. After the trials, the project was "
"discontinued. The prototype did not survive to the present day."

msgid "F107_Hotchkiss_EBR_short"
msgstr "EBR Hotch."

msgid "F108_Panhard_EBR_105"
msgstr "Panhard EBR 105"

msgid "F108_Panhard_EBR_105_descr"
msgstr ""
"A variant of the Panhard EBR armored vehicle with more powerful armament. It "
"featured improved suspension and the two-man GIAT TS 90 turret, upgraded to "
"accommodate a 105 mm gun. The vehicle never saw mass production, nor entered "
"service."

msgid "F108_Panhard_EBR_105_short"
msgstr "EBR 105"

msgid "F109_AMD_Panhard_178B"
msgstr "Panhard AMD 178B"

msgid "F109_AMD_Panhard_178B_descr"
msgstr ""
"Production of the proven Panhard AMD 178 armored vehicle, upgraded with the "
"new FL 1 turret, 47 mm gun SA 35, and coaxial machinegun, was relaunched "
"after World War II. The development of the new turret was started in 1940, "
"but was stopped when France was defeated. The new prototype was designated "
"the Panhard AMD 178B. The produced vehicles saw combat in Indo-China, North "
"Africa, and the Near East."

msgid "F109_AMD_Panhard_178B_short"
msgstr "AMD 178B"

msgid "F10_AMX_50B"
msgstr "AMX 50 B"

msgid "F10_AMX_50B_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed starting in 1951 by DEFA, the state weapons design bureau. By "
"1958, the AMX 50 B received a number of improvements, including a low-"
"profile cast hull and torsion-bar suspension. A new oscillating turret with "
"a 120-mm gun was also mounted on the vehicle. Despite the fact that the "
"Maybach engine power provided just 1,000 h.p., specialists from the German "
"Gruppe M company were looking for a solution that would allow the vehicle to "
"reach a speed of up to 65 km/h. Only one finished prototype of this variant "
"was built."

msgid "F10_AMX_50B_short"
msgstr "AMX 50 B"

msgid "F110_Lynx_6x6"
msgstr "Panhard ERC 90"

msgid "F110_Lynx_6x6_descr"
msgstr ""
"The further development of the Panhard AML armored vehicle with a six-wheel-"
"drive suspension, new turret, and more powerful armament."

msgid "F110_Lynx_6x6_short"
msgstr "ERC 90"

msgid "F111_AM39_Gendron_Somua"
msgstr "AM 39 Gendron-Somua"

msgid "F111_AM39_Gendron_Somua_descr"
msgstr ""
"The first prototype of the armored vehicle was in development from 1932 "
"through 1934 under the supervision of engineer Gendron. The second prototype "
"of 1935 successfully passed trials. The project was almost canceled due to "
"insufficient funds, but the SOMUA company continued its development. An "
"improved prototype was produced in 1938 and successfully underwent trials "
"from 1938 through 1939. It saw service but never entered mass production due "
"to delays with turret supplies."

msgid "F111_AM39_Gendron_Somua_long_special"
msgstr ""
"Quite an unusual vehicle for its tier that reaches key positions in the "
"blink of an eye, and takes advantage of terrain irregularities thanks to "
"decent gun elevation/depression angles. Weak armor dictates extremely "
"cautious gameplay—use your speed to get away and save hit points."

msgid "F111_AM39_Gendron_Somua_short"
msgstr "AM Gendron"

msgid "F111_AM39_Gendron_Somua_short_special"
msgstr "Excellent speed and rate of fire"

msgid "F112_M10_RBFM"
msgstr "M10 RBFM"

msgid "F112_M10_RBFM_descr"
msgstr ""
"The vehicles of this type saw service in the French army from 1943 through "
"1944. In 1944, 36 vehicles of Régiment colonial de chasseurs de chars under "
"the supervision of Silvère Seurat, a naval artillery engineer, featured "
"naval gun sights that allowed for increasing the firing range to 3,000 "
"meters. The famous French actor Jean Gabin (born Jean-Alexis Moncorgé) saw "
"action as a commander of this tank destroyer."

msgid "F112_M10_RBFM_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This tank destroyer features a devastating gun with good depression, "
"balanced by the vehicle's weak armor and large size. It is similar to the "
"M10 Wolverine but cannot boast high mobility due to a less powerful engine. "
"At the same time, the more accurate gun lets it cause damage from long range "
"and avoid being hit."

msgid "F112_M10_RBFM_short"
msgstr "M10 RBFM"

msgid "F112_M10_RBFM_short_special"
msgstr "A powerful gun with more than adequate elevation/depression angles"

msgid "F113_Bretagne_Panther"
msgstr "Bretagne Panther"

msgid "F113_Bretagne_Panther_descr"
msgstr ""
"This Panther modification was produced from August 1943 to June 1944. The "
"Ausf. A modification featured a new turret and bow gun ball mounting. The "
"observation devices also went through modernization. A total of 2,300 "
"vehicles with these modifications were produced. In 1944, after the Allied "
"landing in Normandy, some vehicles were captured by the French Armed Forces "
"and used in combat against the Germans."

msgid "F113_Bretagne_Panther_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This Panther combines all the key characteristics of medium tanks: an "
"accurate gun with a high rate of fire, good mobility with a fast top speed, "
"and a sloped hull with reliable armor plates. But remember the vehicle's "
"large dimensions and keep it safe from enemy fire. Especially, the sides."

msgid "F113_Bretagne_Panther_short"
msgstr "Bret. Panther"

msgid "F113_Bretagne_Panther_short_special"
msgstr "An accurate, rapid-firing gun and good maneuverability."

msgid "F114_Projet_4_1"
msgstr "Char Futur 4"

msgid "F114_Projet_4_1_descr"
msgstr ""
"In 1977, in France, several designs were considered as part of the "
"development of a new tank, including the Projet 4. No metal prototype was "
"produced. However, its further development led to creation of the French "
"main battle tank Leclerc."

msgid "F114_Projet_4_1_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A Tier IX French medium tank with a magazine loading system. Unlike similar "
"vehicles, it boasts an increased number of HP, high armor penetration, and "
"nice accuracy. This tank demonstrates good speed on the battlefield and "
"effective long-range shooting. However, keep in mind its reload time as "
"you'll need to choose your targets carefully."

msgid "F114_Projet_4_1_short"
msgstr "Char Futur 4"

msgid "F114_Projet_4_1_short_special"
msgstr "Magazine loading system and nice penetration"

msgid "F115_Lorraine_50t"
msgstr "Lorraine 50 t"

msgid "F115_Lorraine_50t_descr"
msgstr ""
"A project for a French medium tank developed in the 1950s. It included "
"mounting a 120 mm gun on the hull and chassis of another experimental tank, "
"the Lorraine 40 t, which was being tested at the same time. The project was "
"discontinued at the blueprints stage."

msgid "F115_Lorraine_50t_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A Tier IX heavy tank, continuing the concept of a fast vehicle with high "
"firepower based on the Lorraine 40 t. A sturdy turret with a cyclic gun was "
"mounted on the already familiar suspension. All dynamic characteristics were "
"retained, but its frontal armor was enhanced. However, its main objective "
"remained the same—to support allies."

msgid "F115_Lorraine_50t_short"
msgstr "Lorraine 50 t"

msgid "F115_Lorraine_50t_short_special"
msgstr "Nice dynamics and an accurate gun"

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 12 t bis"

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_DV"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 12 t bis"

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_DV_descr"
msgstr ""
"A French medium tank modified for the urgent delivery of presents and "
"mementos (often explosive). Its crew consists of teddy bears who become "
"anything but cute the moment they enter a tank battle. The vehicle's "
"incredible dynamics and 105 mm gun make it capable of causing unimaginable "
"chaos on the battlefield—while also being the most adorable vehicle in any "
"tanker's collection."

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_DV_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A dynamic tank with a powerful gun featuring a two-shell magazine reloading "
"system. Weak armor and low HP make it hard to fight on the front line. On "
"the other hand, high mobility and speed allow for unexpected outflanking, "
"attacking opponents from the side or rear, and firing two shells and driving "
"back to reload another one."

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_DV_short"
msgstr "B-C 12 t bis"

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_DV_short_special"
msgstr "Good mobility and concealment, effective magazine"

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_descr"
msgstr ""
"A project of a French tank developed by Batignolles-Châtillon. The vehicle "
"was to receive a two-man turret upgraded to accommodate a 105 mm gun. "
"Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A dynamic tank with a powerful gun featuring a two-shell magazine reloading "
"system. Weak armor and low HP make it hard to fight on the front line. On "
"the other hand, high mobility and speed allow for unexpected outflanking, "
"attacking opponents from the side or rear, and firing two shells and driving "
"back to reload another one."

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_short"
msgstr "B-C 12 t bis"

msgid "F116_Bat_Chatillon_Bourrasque_short_special"
msgstr "Good mobility and concealment, effective magazine"

msgid "F117_Alt_Proto_AMX_30"
msgstr "AltProto AMX 30"

msgid "F117_Alt_Proto_AMX_30_descr"
msgstr ""
"In 1958, the AMX company started developing a new medium tank under the "
"Franco-German Standardpanzer (Standard Tank) program. It was supposed to be "
"a 30-ton vehicle with high mobility and a powerful gun. Initially, the "
"project was designated the Char 30 AP and featured a French 105-mm F1 "
"cannon. Over the course of its development, the vehicle was constantly "
"modified and, finally, turned into the AMX 30. The project was discontinued "
"after one scale wooden prototype had been built."

msgid "F117_Alt_Proto_AMX_30_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A Tier VIII French medium tank with decent penetration and good depression/"
"elevation angles. This vehicle features nice dynamics and can take advantage "
"of terrain irregularities due to its reliable gun mantlet. However, keep in "
"mind its low durability and weak armor, and avoid open areas."

msgid "F117_Alt_Proto_AMX_30_short"
msgstr "A.P. AMX 30"

msgid "F117_Alt_Proto_AMX_30_short_special"
msgstr "Good dynamics, depression/elevation angles, and penetration"

msgid "F118_Char_Mle_75"
msgstr "Char Mle. 75"

msgid "F118_Char_Mle_75_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development on this tank began in 1975. It was equipped with a "
"hydropneumatic suspension and support rollers that actually served as the "
"wheels of the armored vehicle. In this sense, the Char Mle. 75 was similar "
"to other promising French armored vehicles. Its turret, as was popular at "
"the time, had the lowest possible profile. As a result, the entire crew was "
"located at hull level. The tank had to be extremely compact and highly "
"maneuverable."

msgid "F118_Char_Mle_75_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A Tier IX Premium French light tank that has two distinctive features at "
"once: a gas-turbine engine, and the mechanics of firing in bursts. Thanks to "
"these particularities, the vehicle perfectly performs the role of a mobile "
"scout and hunter for enemy light tanks."

msgid "F118_Char_Mle_75_short"
msgstr "Char Mle. 75"

msgid "F118_Char_Mle_75_short_special"
msgstr "Mechanics of firing in bursts and a gas-turbine engine"

msgid "F119_Char_Murat"
msgstr "Char Murat"

msgid "F119_Char_Murat_descr"
msgstr ""
"This tank project had two key features—a new fighting compartment "
"configuration and a dual-loop caterpillar propulsion system, which, "
"according to the developers, could boost firepower and mobility. A divider "
"split the fighting compartment into separate crew and gun compartments. The "
"automatic loading system consisted of a main three-shot loading system and "
"an auxiliary mechanized rack. The design made it possible to load the gun "
"and replenish the main rack without setting the gun to a fixed loading "
"angle, significantly increasing the rate of fire and improving the crew's "
"comfort. The track loop was divided into two parts, enabling the vehicle to "
"stay mobile even if it hit a mine. However, the dual-loop propulsion system "
"made the chassis heavier and made the tank more difficult to drive and "
"steer. The project went no further than blueprints."

msgid "F119_Char_Murat_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Char Murat is a Tier IX French medium tank with impressive dynamics and "
"solid firepower thanks to its 105 mm gun featuring a three-shell magazine. "
"Also boasting excellent mobility, decent stabilization, and a quick reload "
"time between shots, the Char Murat excels as a support vehicle, allowing you "
"to engage, unload, and retreat."

msgid "F119_Char_Murat_short"
msgstr "Char Murat"

msgid "F119_Char_Murat_short_special"
msgstr "Magazine loading system, high dynamics and mobility"

msgid "F120_Projet_Louis"
msgstr "Projet Louis"

msgid "F120_Projet_Louis_descr"
msgstr ""
"This experimental light tank had a far-from-classic layout. The engine and "
"main transmission were located at the front, while the cooling system was in "
"the rear. An 880-10 series engine with an inline cylinder arrangement "
"ensured excellent mobility, and the dual-loop caterpillar propulsion system "
"was fitted with two drive wheels. The commander and gunner were located in a "
"compact turret with a low profile and little front and side projection. As "
"with many French developments, the gun could be tilted vertically by raising "
"the turret roof section above the breech. Due to time and financial "
"constraints, the project was closed at the blueprint stage."

msgid "F120_Projet_Louis_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Projet Louis is a Tier IX French light tank with an unusual layout. Its "
"75 mm autoloader has a clip that holds a lot of shells with a very short in-"
"clip reload and a quick full reload. It is built for near-constant fire, "
"dealing small but steady damage to enemies."

msgid "F120_Projet_Louis_short"
msgstr "Projet Louis"

msgid "F120_Projet_Louis_short_special"
msgstr "Autoloader, good mobility"

msgid "F122_VCS_6x6_TS90"
msgstr "VCS 6x6 TS 90"

msgid "F122_VCS_6x6_TS90_descr"
msgstr ""
"The VCS 6x6 TS 90 was developed for export as a recon vehicle that could "
"engage in combat with tanks. The design was harmonized as much as possible "
"with the Renault VAB armored personnel carrier. The vehicle was presented to "
"the press in June 1976; however, it never entered mass production. The "
"project led to the development of the VBC-90."

msgid "F122_VCS_6x6_TS90_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The VCS 6x6 TS 90 is a Tier IX French wheeled light tank that has excellent "
"mobility with high top forward and reverse speeds. The tank lacks dual "
"driving modes and the need to switch between them. It is armed with a 90 mm "
"stabilized gun with good aiming time and a 2-shell magazine with an "
"incredibly fast intra-clip reload of 1.5 seconds."

msgid "F122_VCS_6x6_TS90_short"
msgstr "VCS 6x6"

msgid "F122_VCS_6x6_TS90_short_special"
msgstr "Wheeled vehicle, 2-shell magazine"

msgid "F123_ERAC_105_Proto"
msgstr "ERAC 105 Proto"

msgid "F123_ERAC_105_Proto_descr"
msgstr ""
"A project for an amphibious armored reconnaissance vehicle (French: engin de "
"reconnaissance amphibie de combat) from the early 1960s. A working prototype "
"was built in 1963. The vehicle had a low weight together with significant "
"firepower, and it could ford wet gaps. Its advantages included fairly high "
"crossing capacity over mud and snow, while its aluminum alloy hull offered "
"better protection than most amphibious vehicles had at that time. In spite "
"of positive results from trials, the ERAC 105 Proto did not enter service "
"due to economic reasons."

msgid "F123_ERAC_105_Proto_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The ERAC 105 Proto is a Tier IX French light tank with an impressive -8° of "
"gun depression. Its compact size makes it an excellent passive scout, while "
"its great accuracy and decent DPM allow it to deal damage effectively. With "
"a 105 mm gun, it is one of the hardest-hitting lights of its tier."

msgid "F123_ERAC_105_Proto_short"
msgstr "ERAC 105 Pr"

msgid "F123_ERAC_105_Proto_short_special"
msgstr "High alpha damage, compact size"

msgid "F124_AMX_13FL11"
msgstr "AMX 13 (FL 11)"

msgid "F124_AMX_13FL11_descr"
msgstr ""
"Despite demands to send the new AMX-13 tank to Indochina, it was not well-"
"suited to that theater of operations: Its turret and gun were too large, "
"while its autoloader was expensive, difficult to maintain, and virtually "
"useless—the enemy had almost no armored vehicles. Moreover, what was needed "
"was a lighter tank that could be transported by air. As a result, the AMX-13 "
"was equipped with the FL-11 turret from the Panhard EBR armored vehicle "
"without an autoloader gun. The lack of autoloader allowed for the use of a "
"more varied range of ammunition to support infantry units. A total of 20 "
"vehicles were ordered, but only five were actually produced. After the end "
"of hostilities in Vietnam in 1954, the remaining tanks were redeployed to "
"Morocco, where they saw out their combat career."

msgid "F124_AMX_13FL11_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This hybrid tank features the hull from the AMX 13 and the FL 11 turret from "
"the Panhard EBR armored vehicle. It is armed with a classic 75 mm gun, with "
"almost the same characteristics as the 75 mm guns of other French light "
"tanks. It also boasts excellent mobility, high top forward/reverse speed, "
"and good concealment."

msgid "F124_AMX_13FL11_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 FL 11"

msgid "F124_AMX_13FL11_short_special"
msgstr "Good concealment and excellent mobility"

msgid "F127_AMX_ELC_901"
msgstr "AMX ELC 901"

msgid "F127_AMX_ELC_901_descr"
msgstr ""
"The ELC AMX 901 was the first prototype of a tank being designed under the "
"Engin Léger de Combat (light combat vehicle) program. Tests done in 1955 "
"revealed many design flaws. An improved version of the tank—the AMX ELC 90 "
"bis—was thoroughly reworked and given all necessary alterations. It differed "
"greatly from the prototype and was essentially a brand-new vehicle."

msgid "F127_AMX_ELC_901_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The AMX ELC 901 is a Tier VI French light tank, essentially a variant of the "
"researchable AMX ELC bis. It shares the same advantages: an extremely low "
"silhouette, excellent concealment, and great mobility. Equipped with a 90 mm "
"gun, its turret rotation is limited to 30° due to its small size."

msgid "F127_AMX_ELC_901_short"
msgstr "AMX ELC 901"

msgid "F127_AMX_ELC_901_short_special"
msgstr "Big alpha damage, excellent concealment"

msgid "F128_SFAC_105"
msgstr "SFAC 105"

msgid "F128_SFAC_105_descr"
msgstr ""
"After World War II, France received many German designs for armored "
"vehicles, including documentation for tank destroyers of the Waffenträger "
"family, as well as versatile combat vehicles with double-barreled gun "
"systems. As a result of studying the data, the French created a whole family "
"of tank destroyers. One of them was the SFAC 105, which had good mobility "
"and two anti-air guns. However, the project did not reach the prototype "
"phase. Instead of mobile tank destroyers, France began developing self-"
"propelled howitzers."

msgid "F128_SFAC_105_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A French light armored tank destroyer featuring a double-barreled gun "
"system. Its experimental aiming device grants quick aiming and enhanced "
"accuracy, while its quick gun-changing time means the SFAC 105 operates like "
"a two-shell magazine. However, despite its excellent mobility, the vehicle "
"only has basic protection."

msgid "F128_SFAC_105_short"
msgstr "SFAC 105"

msgid "F128_SFAC_105_short_special"
msgstr "Double-barreled system, good mobility"

msgid "F129_ARL_44_BPXIV"
msgstr "Char de transition"

msgid "F129_ARL_44_BPXIV_descr"
msgstr ""
"We knew that the occupation could not last forever. Come on, did they really "
"think that the people of France would accept it? Impossible. There is a "
"reason why the whole world knows about the French Revolution. Nobody can "
"make us live in that way, as if we will just obey every command our 'master' "
"gives us. To be French is to love freedom. So when they were trying to take "
"it away from us this time, even in the darkest hours, I always believed in "
"France. And when the battle came at Normandy, as a Normand, I knew that it "
"was the time—the time to show who we are and what we stand for."

msgid "F129_ARL_44_BPXIV_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This experimental heavy took part in the Normandy landings during World War "
"II. French engineers struggled to come up with a reliable heavy at the time, "
"and only single prototypes were deployed on the battlefield. This one was "
"approved for limited service and later put into mass production just before "
"the end of the Second World War."

msgid "F129_ARL_44_BPXIV_short"
msgstr "CDT"

msgid "F129_ARL_44_BPXIV_short_special"
msgstr "Powerful gun, good frontal armor"

msgid "F130_Sentinelle"
msgstr "Char Lourd 60 t"

msgid "F130_Sentinelle_descr"
msgstr ""
"A joint project of the Italian and French defense ministries that was given "
"the name Char Lourd 60 t. The Char Lourd AP 58 was used as the basis for the "
"vehicle and the turret and armament were Italian, while the optics and comms "
"equipment were French. The tank was intended to have a fairly low silhouette "
"and powerful armament. However, due to ammo standardization under NATO, the "
"vehicle was no longer needed. The project was terminated before a prototype "
"was built."

msgid "F130_Sentinelle_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Char Lourd 60 t is a Tier IX French heavy tank, but its mobility, size, and "
"armor resemble those of a medium tank—only the turret front is well-armored. "
"Its main feature is a fast two-shell magazine with good handling and 390 HP "
"of damage per shot. Its small size, good mobility, and decent gun depression "
"make it effective from medium tank positions."

msgid "F130_Sentinelle_short"
msgstr "Char Lourd 60 t"

msgid "F130_Sentinelle_short_special"
msgstr "Fast autoloader, good mobility"

msgid "F131_Brennos"
msgstr "AMX M4 47"

msgid "F131_Brennos_descr"
msgstr ""
"After World War II, the French decided to create a heavy tank taking into "
"account their accumulated experience. All pre-war and wartime French heavy "
"tank projects were taken into consideration. A clear German influence could "
"be sensed in many parts and components, since France had abundant "
"information on the Panther and the King Tiger. The French even considered "
"borrowing ideas from the U.S.S.R., attempting to reproduce the famous pike "
"nose of the IS-3 on the new vehicle. Although the turret was reminiscent of "
"the King Tiger's, a cast one was planned with additional French know-how in "
"the form of a commander's cupola with two 20 mm cannons. In the course of "
"detailed development it became clear that the concept of the tank was "
"outdated and that, should it enter mass production, it would no longer be "
"relevant. The project went no further than blueprints."

msgid "F131_Brennos_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The AMX M4 47 has a comfortable gun for a Tier VIII heavy, with great "
"stabilization, penetration power, and aiming time. Its powerful engine "
"enables quick acceleration and short sprints. However, the tank has mediocre "
"hull armor and large turret weak spots."

msgid "F131_Brennos_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 47"

msgid "F131_Brennos_short_special"
msgstr "Great stabilization, good penetration power"

msgid "F132_Vercingetorix"
msgstr "FCM 60 t"

msgid "F132_Vercingetorix_descr"
msgstr ""
"A project developed in the mid-1950s as an alternative to the AMX 50 "
"program. The hull was designed to be as low as possible, and many of the "
"technical solutions already contained elements of the future AMX 30. "
"However, provisional estimates showed that ensuring reliable armor and "
"installing modern weaponry would take the tank up to 60 tons, which "
"significantly exceed the requirements of the military clients. The tank was "
"never built."

msgid "F132_Vercingetorix_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The FCM 60 t is a Tier IX French medium tank with armor, armament, and "
"mobility closer to a heavy. It has reliable turret armor and a 120 mm gun "
"suitable for close combat. Its key feature is a gas-turbine engine enabling "
"Rapid mode, turning it into a true medium tank for fast repositioning."

msgid "F132_Vercingetorix_short"
msgstr "FCM 60 t"

msgid "F132_Vercingetorix_short_special"
msgstr "Gas-turbine engine, reliable turret armor"

msgid "F134_Lorraine_120_Alby"
msgstr "Lorraine 120"

msgid "F134_Lorraine_120_Alby_descr"
msgstr ""
"An SPG with a cabin arrangement, combining high protection and firepower in "
"the most compact possible dimensions and a weight of 45 tons. One of the "
"main goals in the vehicle's development was to increase traverse limits "
"without any turning of the hull. This led to a new design for the fighting "
"compartment. The project called for mounting a 105 mm or 120 mm rifled gun. "
"A muzzle brake was even planned for the latter.\n"
"Creation of a prototype brought to light numerous disadvantages. The "
"mobility was fairly mediocre, and fuel consumption was enormous. Mounting "
"the large guns was also difficult, since the barrel had an overhang of more "
"than four meters, creating problems when traversing rough terrain and "
"demanding greater attention from the driver. Also, the heavy weight and "
"large size of the 120 mm gun overloaded the front end of the vehicle and led "
"to rapid wear and tear of the front support units. Work on the project was "
"canceled."

msgid "F134_Lorraine_120_Alby_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Lorraine 120 is a French Tier VIII tank destroyer. It follows "
"classic French TD principles: a low profile, good mobility, solid front "
"armor, and a 120 mm autoloading gun. Its key feature is a movable "
"superstructure with the gun, allowing 30° traverse to each side without "
"shifting the hull."

msgid "F134_Lorraine_120_Alby_short"
msgstr "Lorraine 120"

msgid "F134_Lorraine_120_Alby_short_special"
msgstr "Autoloader, good frontal armor"

msgid "F135_AS_XX_40_t"
msgstr "AS-XX 40 t"

msgid "F135_AS_XX_40_t_descr"
msgstr ""
"A prototype of a French medium tank developed in 1978 as part of a program "
"to research new configuration options. The main idea of the vehicle was to "
"ensure maximum crew safety. For this purpose, the gun and ammunition were "
"located outside of the fighting compartment, which lowered the risk of "
"injury. In case of fire, the crew could release the burning crate using a "
"pyrocartridge. Most ammo was located in a mechanized rack on the gun and was "
"automatically replenished from two armored crates in the rear. Since the "
"development was so complex and labor-intensive, it stopped at the wooden "
"mockup stage."

msgid "F135_AS_XX_40_t_long_special"
msgstr ""
"Building on the strengths of its predecessors, the AS-XX 40 t is a highly "
"mobile medium tank. Equipped with an autoloading gun that's always primed to "
"engage, its compact profile and quick acceleration make it a dependable "
"support vehicle. It excels at unexpected flanking maneuvers—but its limited "
"survivability demands caution before making any bold moves."

msgid "F135_AS_XX_40_t_short"
msgstr "AS-XX 40 t"

msgid "F136_AMX_67_Imbattable"
msgstr "AMX 67"

msgid "F136_AMX_67_Imbattable_descr"
msgstr ""
"Toward the end of the 1960s, the French were using modern AMX-30 tanks "
"capable of effective resistance against armored vehicles of a potential "
"enemy. At the same time, they were developing vehicles with more impressive "
"armor, among which was the AMX 67. The tank was notable for its "
"powerful armament capable of striking targets a long range, as well as a "
"high fire rate. The vehicle's key feature was placement of the gun in a low-"
"profile turret with an overhead weapon station equipped with an autoloader. "
"The project existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F136_AMX_67_Imbattable_long_special"
msgstr ""
"Unusually for a heavy tank, the AMX 67 trades reliable armor for "
"impressive mobility and a well-balanced autoloading gun. On the battlefield, "
"it excels in a supporting role, assisting allies with concentrated fire when "
"it matters most—with its experimental loading system ensuring it remains "
"ready to strike at a moment's notice."

msgid "F136_AMX_67_Imbattable_short"
msgstr "AMX 67"

msgid "F137_LEOX"
msgstr "Proyecto LEOX"

msgid "F137_LEOX_descr"
msgstr ""
"In 1970, Spain ran into problems as its fleet of American tanks, including "
"the M74, had become outdated. For political reasons, the U.S.A. and U.K. "
"were unable to ship arms to the kingdom, as was Germany, since the gun of "
"the German Leopard 1 was British. As a result, Spain purchased the French "
"AMX 30 and from 1974 began production of a licensed version, the AMX 30E, "
"which was not modernized. The French tanks proved insufficiently reliable, "
"and so Spain had to modernize the old M47, M48, and AMX 30. In 1979, after "
"AMX 30E production ended, modernization projects began, including the El Niño"
"—the AMX 30 with an elongated hull—and the Leox—a modification of the "
"Leopard 1 hull with the AMX 30E turret."

msgid "F137_LEOX_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Proyecto LEOX is a Tier IX French medium tank. It boasts a powerful engine which "
"allows the vehicle to achieve impressive speeds, repositioning to any part "
"of the battlefield at short notice. Additionally, the vehicle’s accurate gun "
"allows it to inflict critical damage to a vast number of enemies from all "
"possible ranges."

msgid "F137_LEOX_short"
msgstr "Proyecto LEOX"

msgid "F137_LEOX_short_special"
msgstr "Impressive top speed, high penetration"

msgid "F138_Renault_R35_FCM_36"
msgstr "Renault R35/FCM 36"

msgid "F138_Renault_R35_FCM_36_desc"
msgstr ""
"As part of a 1930s program to develop and produce new tanks, France was "
"actively working to unify the turrets of different vehicles. One such "
"experimental project was the R35 light tank with the turret of the FCM 36. "
"The vehicle never entered mass production."

msgid "F138_Renault_R35_FCM_36_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Renault R35/FCM 36 is a Tier II French light tank. It combines the hull "
"of the Renault R35 with the turret of the FCM 36. The tank has a 37 mm gun "
"with an exceptionally high rate of fire and good, reliable armor. This "
"combination of characteristics allows the vehicle to hold key positions and "
"push through enemy shots."

msgid "F138_Renault_R35_FCM_36_short"
msgstr "R35/FCM 36"

msgid "F138_Renault_R35_FCM_36_short_special"
msgstr "Good armor, high rate of fire"

msgid "F139_Terrifiant"
msgstr "Terrifiant"

msgid "F139_Terrifiant_descr"
msgstr ""
"In the 1950s, French heavy tank development reached a dead end. Several "
"attempts to develop designs from WWII failed to produce competitive new "
"vehicles, so France turned to the U.S.A. for help. They purchased documents "
"and blueprints for the suspension of the TS-6 heavy tank project, which was "
"never built. The French designers mounted a turret equipped with a 128 mm "
"gun on top. The resulting tank was too heavy, and efforts to install a "
"powerful engine of over 1,000 h.p. failed. The project was discontinued."

msgid "F139_Terrifiant_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Terrifiant is a Tier IX French heavy tank. It is reminiscent of French "
"heavy tanks with its strong frontal hull and turret armor, a punchy gun "
"dealing high damage per shot with decent accuracy, and respectable mobility."

msgid "F139_Terrifiant_short"
msgstr "Terrifiant"

msgid "F139_Terrifiant_short_special"
msgstr "Reliable frontal armor, high single damage"

msgid "F13_AMX38"
msgstr "AMX 38"

msgid "F13_AMX38_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed in 1937–1938 under the \"20-ton vehicle\" project and was intended "
"to replace the D2 tank. The project included two turret variants: with a 37-"
"mm or a 47-mm gun. By 1938, two vehicles were built for trials. Never saw "
"mass production."

msgid "F13_AMX38_short"
msgstr "AMX 38"

msgid "F140_Fantome"
msgstr "Fantôme"

msgid "F140_Fantome_descr"
msgstr ""
"From 1963 through 1964, Porsche developed a prospective tank for the 1970s, "
"which was ultimately rejected. Later, this project ended up in France, where "
"the Creusot-Loire company proposed it as a unified tank for France, Germany, "
"and eventually other countries. However, the vehicle turned out too "
"expensive, which was a decisive factor in the project's closure."

msgid "F140_Fantome_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Fantôme is a Tier IX French medium tank which has all the familiar "
"French features, such as good mobility and an autoloading gun. But what "
"separates it from the rest is automatic hydropneumatic suspension, which "
"allows the vehicle to reach greater gun depression and elevation angles, "
"enhancing its efficiency on uneven terrain."

msgid "F140_Fantome_short"
msgstr "Fantôme"

msgid "F140_Fantome_short_special"
msgstr "Autoloader, automatic hydropneumatic suspension"

msgid "F141_Durendal"
msgstr "Durendal"

msgid "F141_Durendal_desc"
msgstr ""
"A preliminary design for a medium tank based on Franco-Italian developments."

msgid "F141_Durendal_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The Durendal is a Tier X French support medium tank. It possesses an unusual "
"autoloading gun that has two containers delivering very quick two-shell "
"bursts. This allows it to inflict significant damage in a short amount of "
"time. It also has exceptional mobility, enabling it to strike from "
"unexpected angles."

msgid "F141_Durendal_short"
msgstr "Durendal"

msgid "F141_Durendal_short_special"
msgstr "Autoloader with containers, good mobility"

msgid "F143_Fauteur"
msgstr "AMX M4 70"

msgid "F143_Fauteur_descr"
msgstr ""
"In the early 1970s, AMX promoted a program to develop a new highly armored "
"tank, armed with a powerful, fast-firing gun. Although the armor was "
"traditional, the firepower was based on a new principle. The engineers "
"planned to implement a hybrid gun with additional electrical power "
"increasing the effectiveness of the solid propellant. The propellant gases "
"were heated by an electric arc between electrodes on the barrel, improving "
"combustion and boosting the shot power. The project was closed due to "
"technical limitations."

msgid "F143_Fauteur_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The AMX M4 70 is the product of a reliable heavy tank formula and advanced "
"propellant manipulations, giving a formidable vehicle that is well-suited to "
"both close- and long-range combat. Good armor lets it withstand enemy fire, "
"while decent mobility gets its firepower closer to the front lines."

msgid "F143_Fauteur_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 70"

msgid "F14_AMX40"
msgstr "AMX 40"

msgid "F14_AMX40_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development started in March 1940. Almost all armor plates had a complex and "
"curvilinear shape, and the hull featured few, if any, right angles. The AMX "
"40 was supposed to replace the Somua S35 and S40 in 1941–1942, but the "
"project was discontinued in July 1940. Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F14_AMX40_short"
msgstr "AMX 40"

msgid "F15_AMX_12t"
msgstr "AMX 12 t"

msgid "F15_AMX_12t_descr"
msgstr ""
"This design of a light high-speed tank was developed in 1946. The vehicle "
"was never actually produced, but became the basis for the well-known AMX 13."

msgid "F15_AMX_12t_short"
msgstr "AMX 12 t"

msgid "F16_AMX_13_75"
msgstr "AMX 13 75"

msgid "F16_AMX_13_75_descr"
msgstr ""
"Maneuverable light tank with an oscillating turret and a 75 mm autoloader "
"gun that could fire up to 10 shots per minute. At that time, the gun on this "
"vehicle had superior penetration compared to the guns of most other medium "
"tanks."

msgid "F16_AMX_13_75_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 75"

msgid "F17_AMX_13_90"
msgstr "AMX 13 90"

msgid "F17_AMX_13_90_descr"
msgstr ""
"In the early 1960s, the 75-mm gun with a muzzle velocity of 1,000 m/s was "
"deemed outdated. The vehicle received the new 90-mm F3 gun that used more "
"powerful HEAT shells. This modernization did not require any significant "
"changes to the turret or vehicle design. The first vehicles were "
"manufactured in February, 1967. The existing vehicles underwent the gun "
"modernization as well."

msgid "F17_AMX_13_90_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 90"

msgid "F18_Bat_Chatillon25t"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 25 t"

msgid "F18_Bat_Chatillon25t_7x7"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 25 t 7x7"

msgid "F18_Bat_Chatillon25t_7x7_descr"
msgstr ""
"A medium tank with an oscillating turret and a 90 mm gun. Developed by "
"Batignolles-Châtillon in the mid-1950s. Two prototypes were manufactured. "
"The vehicle never entered mass production."

msgid "F18_Bat_Chatillon25t_7x7_short"
msgstr "B-C 25 t 7x7"

msgid "F18_Bat_Chatillon25t_descr"
msgstr ""
"A medium tank with an oscillating turret and a 90 mm gun. Developed by "
"Batignolles-Châtillon in the mid-1950s. Two prototypes were manufactured. "
"The vehicle never entered mass production."

msgid "F18_Bat_Chatillon25t_short"
msgstr "B-C 25 t"

msgid "F19_Lorraine40t"
msgstr "Lorraine 40 t"

msgid "F19_Lorraine40t_descr"
msgstr ""
"This experimental French tank was developed during the 1940s. Two prototypes "
"were manufactured in 1952. In addition to the oscillating turret, the "
"vehicle featured suspension with air-core tires and pike nose armor. The "
"design passed trials, but never entered mass production."

msgid "F19_Lorraine40t_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A very swift medium tank with a 4-shell magazine that can potentially deal "
"1,200 HP of damage in a short time. Its high maneuverability is somewhat "
"balanced by its mediocre armor, which makes sudden flank attacks the best "
"strategy for the vehicle."

msgid "F19_Lorraine40t_short"
msgstr "Lorr. 40 t"

msgid "F19_Lorraine40t_short_special"
msgstr "A magazine reloading system and excellent mobility"

msgid "F22_AMX_105AM"
msgstr "AMX 13 105 AM mle. 50"

msgid "F22_AMX_105AM_descr"
msgstr ""
"The development of a self-propelled gun on the basis of the AMX 13 75 was "
"started in the late 1940s. The vehicle featured the Obusier de 105 mm TF50 "
"howitzer. In the early 1950s, the SPG saw service in the French army. A "
"total of 429 vehicles were produced; 92 of them were exported to the "
"Netherlands."

msgid "F22_AMX_105AM_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 AM"

msgid "F23_AMX_13F3AM"
msgstr "AMX 13 F3 AM"

msgid "F23_AMX_13F3AM_descr"
msgstr ""
"At the end of the 1950s, engineers of Creusot-Loire developed the new "
"vehicle on the shortened basis of the AMX 13. The vehicle featured a 155-mm "
"gun. It was mass-produced from 1962 through 1997 with a total of 600 "
"vehicles manufactured. The SPG is still in service in France, Argentina, "
"Chile, Ecuador, Morocco, and other countries."

msgid "F23_AMX_13F3AM_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 F3"

msgid "F24_Lorraine155_50"
msgstr "Lorraine 155 mle. 50"

msgid "F24_Lorraine155_50_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed in France after the war on the basis of the experimental Lorraine "
"40 t. The vehicle passed trials in 1950, but never entered mass production "
"or saw service."

msgid "F24_Lorraine155_50_short"
msgstr "Lorr. 155 50"

msgid "F25_Lorraine155_51"
msgstr "Lorraine 155 mle. 51"

msgid "F25_Lorraine155_51_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed in 1951 based on the Lorraine 40 t and featured a 155-mm howitzer. "
"The prototype passed trials simultaneously with the tank, but the Lorraine "
"40 t did not see service, and the SPG project was discontinued as well."

msgid "F25_Lorraine155_51_short"
msgstr "Lorr. 155 51"

msgid "F27_FCM_36Pak40_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A Tier III French tank destroyer with a powerful, accurate gun and a great "
"view range that allows you to quickly spot and destroy enemy vehicles. Due "
"to its mediocre armor, you should take defensive positions, stay behind "
"cover, and fire over medium or long distances."

msgid "F27_FCM_36Pak40_short_special"
msgstr "A decent gun and a great view range"

msgid "F32_Somua_Sau_40"
msgstr "Somua SAu 40"

msgid "F32_Somua_Sau_40_descr"
msgstr ""
"A project for an SPG to support light mechanized units. Designed from 1935 "
"through 1937 on the basis of the S35 and S40 vehicles. The design featured a "
"modified upper part of the armored hull with the 75-mm casemate Mle 1929 "
"gun. The top of the cabin featured a single-seated turret with the 7,5-mm "
"Mle 1931 machinegun. The mass production of the SAu 40 was requested in "
"October 1939. A prototype (and, according to some historical sources, four "
"more pilot SAu 40) were sent to the frontline and used in action in June "
"1940."

msgid "F32_Somua_Sau_40_short"
msgstr "SAu 40"

msgid "F33_S_35CA"
msgstr "S35 CA"

msgid "F33_S_35CA_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed on the basis of the obsolete R35 and S35 vehicles. The simple "
"design allowed the open cabin with a British 17-pounder gun to be mounted on "
"the chassis. However, the project was discontinued during the design phase "
"due to a shortage and obsolescence of pre-war chassis, as well as an "
"ineffective and unconventional gun."

msgid "F33_S_35CA_short"
msgstr "S35 CA"

msgid "F34_ARL_V39"
msgstr "ARL V39"

msgid "F34_ARL_V39_descr"
msgstr ""
"A prototype of the ARL 40. The vehicle was intended as an assault SPG. Mass "
"production was to be launched in 1940 but never started due to the "
"occupation of France."

msgid "F34_ARL_V39_short"
msgstr "ARL V39"

msgid "F35_AMX_AC_Mle1946"
msgstr "AMX AC mle. 46"

msgid "F35_AMX_AC_Mle1946_descr"
msgstr ""
"Proposed plan for a heavy tank destroyer on the basis of the M4. Development "
"was started in 1946. The configuration of the vehicle had a strong "
"resemblance to the Jagdpanther. Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F35_AMX_AC_Mle1946_short"
msgstr "AMX AC 46"

msgid "F36_AMX_AC_Mle1948"
msgstr "AMX AC mle. 48"

msgid "F36_AMX_AC_Mle1948_FL"
msgstr "AMX AC mle. 48 FL"

msgid "F36_AMX_AC_Mle1948_FL_short"
msgstr "AMX AC 48 FL"

msgid "F36_AMX_AC_Mle1948_descr"
msgstr ""
"A draft project of a heavy tank destroyer, developed in 1947–1948 under the "
"influence of the Jagdpanther. The vehicle was to feature a 120 mm gun as the "
"main armament. The distinctive feature of the vehicle was three 20 mm MG "
"151/20 machineguns, mounted on top of the fighting compartment and rear. "
"Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F36_AMX_AC_Mle1948_short"
msgstr "AMX AC 48"

msgid "F37_AMX50_Foch"
msgstr "AMX 50 Foch"

msgid "F37_AMX50_Foch_descr"
msgstr ""
"From the late 1940s to the early 1950s, France was developing heavy tank "
"destroyers. This project was developed under the influence of German tank "
"destroyers of WWII. The vehicle featured a 120-mm gun. At least one "
"prototype was built, which took part in the military parade in Paris on July "
"14, 1950. Never saw mass production."

msgid "F37_AMX50_Foch_short"
msgstr "Foch"

msgid "F38_Bat_Chatillon155_58"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 155 58"

msgid "F38_Bat_Chatillon155_58_descr"
msgstr ""
"An experimental project for an SPG that used some elements of the U.S. M47 "
"chassis. As compared to the Bat.-Châtillon 155 55, the vehicle had a "
"different turret and featured the magazine loading system. Existed only in "
"blueprints."

msgid "F38_Bat_Chatillon155_58_short"
msgstr "B-C 155 58"

msgid "F39_AMR_P103"
msgstr "AMR P.103"

msgid "F39_AMR_P103_descr"
msgstr ""
"A light tank developed in 1935 by Citroën engineers. The vehicle underwent "
"trials in April of the same year, which showed that the main components and "
"crew had reliable protection. However, due to the unreliability of the "
"chassis and hydraulic transmission, as well as low speed, the project was "
"dropped in favor of the AMR 35. The only prototype was subsequently "
"dismantled."

msgid "F39_AMR_P103_long_special"
msgstr ""
"The AMR P.103 is a universal Tier II light tank with solid mobility, "
"allowing it to quickly reach key positions on the battlefield. Its gun "
"offers a high rate of fire, while its good view range makes it effective at "
"spotting enemies—especially in the later stages of battle."

msgid "F39_AMR_P103_short"
msgstr "AMR P.103"

msgid "F39_AMR_P103_short_special"
msgstr "Good view range, high rate of fire"

msgid "F42_AMR_35"
msgstr "AMR 35"

msgid "F42_AMR_35_descr"
msgstr ""
"A light reconnaissance tank developed by Renault. A total of 200 vehicles "
"with different modifications were produced from 1936 through 1940. This tank "
"fought in the early stages of WWII. After the capitulation of France, the "
"majority of these vehicles were captured by the Germans and converted into "
"self-propelled vehicles with 8 cm mortars."

msgid "F42_AMR_35_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A tank with small dimensions and a reliable gun for its tier. It doesn't "
"boast high speed or decent armor, so it's a good idea to rely on concealment "
"instead. Its low silhouette makes this tank harder to detect and hit. In "
"addition, its good depression/elevation angles allow for the effective use "
"of terrain irregularities."

msgid "F42_AMR_35_short"
msgstr "AMR 35"

msgid "F42_AMR_35_short_special"
msgstr "A good gun and excellent concealment"

msgid "F44_Somua_S35"
msgstr "Somua S35"

msgid "F44_Somua_S35_descr"
msgstr ""
"Good firepower, armor protection, and mobility made the S35 one of the best "
"tanks of its time. However, the small turret forced the commander to handle "
"multiple tasks at once: searching for enemy targets, aiming and reloading "
"the gun, and coordinating the actions of the crew. This workload reduced his "
"situational awareness and decreased the vehicle’s effectiveness on the "
"battlefield. By the time France capitulated on June 22, 1940, a total of 427 "
"vehicles had been manufactured."

msgid "F44_Somua_S35_short"
msgstr "Somua S35"

msgid "F50_FCM36_20t"
msgstr "FCM 36"

msgid "F50_FCM36_20t_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed in the mid-1930s as an infantry-support tank. It was the only "
"French vehicle to utilize a diesel engine. By 1939, a total of 100 vehicles "
"were manufactured."

msgid "F50_FCM36_20t_short"
msgstr "FCM 36"

msgid "F62_ELC_AMX"
msgstr "AMX ELC bis"

msgid "F62_ELC_AMX_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed from 1957 through 1961 to provide French airborne troops with an "
"air-transportable vehicle that could engage heavy tanks. The vehicle mounted "
"a 90-mm gun and had a very low silhouette. The two crew members were seated "
"in the turret, which could turn through 360 degrees, but only when the "
"vehicle was not moving. Variants with different guns were planned. Only one "
"prototype was manufactured. The vehicle never saw service."

msgid "F62_ELC_AMX_short"
msgstr "AMX ELC bis"

msgid "F64_AMX_50Fosh_B"
msgstr "AMX 50 Foch B"

msgid "F64_AMX_50Fosh_B_7x7"
msgstr "AMX 50 Foch B 7v7"

msgid "F64_AMX_50Fosh_B_7x7_short"
msgstr "Foch B 7v7"

msgid "F64_AMX_50Fosh_B_descr"
msgstr ""
"The project of the AMX 50 Foch tank destroyer with a 120 mm gun provided for "
"installing the automatic loading system. However, after work on the AMX 50 "
"120 with the same armament started, the project was deemed potentially "
"inefficient. Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F64_AMX_50Fosh_B_short"
msgstr "Foch B"

msgid "F67_Bat_Chatillon155_55"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 155 55"

msgid "F67_Bat_Chatillon155_55_descr"
msgstr ""
"In the mid-50s, Batignolles-Châtillon developed an original design of the "
"heavy SPG that featured some elements of the U.S. M47 chassis. The vehicle "
"was equipped with a 155 mm howitzer installed into the rotating turret. At "
"least one prototype was built. Never saw mass production."

msgid "F67_Bat_Chatillon155_55_short"
msgstr "B-C 155 55"

msgid "F68_AMX_Chasseur_de_char_46"
msgstr "AMX Chasseur de chars"

msgid "F68_AMX_Chasseur_de_char_46_descr"
msgstr ""
"In 1946, the AMX company presented this design for a new vehicle. The "
"powerful engine and light weight would have made the vehicle highly mobile, "
"and the 90-mm gun was equipped with a mechanical ammunition system for a "
"high rate of fire. However, the large dimensions of the vehicle, its thin "
"armor, high cost, and the complexity of the design made it unappealing, and "
"the project never advanced to a prototype."

msgid "F68_AMX_Chasseur_de_char_46_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This is one of the fastest vehicles in its tier. Moreover, it is equipped "
"with a perfect gun. Its speed compensates for its weak armor, which makes "
"the vehicle vulnerable to any hit. But this is still a hard target to hit!"

msgid "F68_AMX_Chasseur_de_char_46_short"
msgstr "AMX CDC"

msgid "F68_AMX_Chasseur_de_char_46_short_special"
msgstr "A reliable gun, perfect speed, and a good view range"

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100"
msgstr "AMX 13 57"

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_GrandFinal"
msgstr "AMX 13 57 GF"

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_GrandFinal_descr"
msgstr ""
"The AMX company conceived this light tank, which was to mount the 57-mm L/"
"100 gun. Problems in development slowed the project, and by the 1950s the "
"vehicle was still not ready for presentation. By that time, the production "
"of a modified chassis with the turret mounting a 75-mm gun had taken "
"precedence, and the 57-mm version was discontinued."

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_GrandFinal_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This light tank is equipped with a gun that features a magazine reloading "
"system with enormous damage potential. It is best used in close combat—its "
"eight shells cause a huge amount of damage in a short period of time."

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_GrandFinal_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 57F"

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_GrandFinal_short_special"
msgstr "A unique gun and decent mobility"

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_descr"
msgstr ""
"The AMX company conceived this light tank, which was to mount the 57-mm L/"
"100 gun. Problems in development slowed the project, and by the 1950s the "
"vehicle was still not ready for presentation. By that time, the production "
"of a modified chassis with the turret mounting a 75-mm gun had taken "
"precedence, and the 57-mm version was discontinued."

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This French light tank is equipped with a gun that features a magazine "
"reloading system with enormous damage potential. It is best used in close "
"combat—its eight shells cause a huge amount of damage in a short period of "
"time."

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 57"

msgid "F69_AMX13_57_100_short_special"
msgstr "High accuracy and rate of fire"

msgid "F72_AMX_30"
msgstr "AMX 30 B"

msgid "F72_AMX_30_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed in 1966. The vehicle had maneuverability, engine power, and "
"effective anti-tank engagement distance superior to all other vehicles "
"except the Leopard 1. Great view range allowed the vehicle’s commander to "
"coordinate the actions of the crew and to maintain situational awareness, "
"greatly increasing the vehicle’s effectiveness. The armor of the vehicle was "
"quite thin, but it was decided that technological advances in anti-tank "
"shells had essentially rendered armor obsolete: survivability would depend "
"on mobility and firepower. A total of 2,800 vehicles were manufactured."

msgid "F72_AMX_30_short"
msgstr "AMX 30 B"

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise"
msgstr "M4A1 Revalorisé"

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise_FL"
msgstr "M4A1 Revalorisé FL"

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise_FL_short"
msgstr "M4A1 Rev. FL"

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise_descr"
msgstr ""
"In the 1950s, the M4 Sherman of various modifications was supplied to France "
"as part of MDAP. French design bureaus started modernizing the vehicle with "
"the goal of improving its firepower. This initiative was followed by a "
"modernization program for the Israel Defense Forces (Sherman M51). The tank "
"never saw service in France. The number of prototypes built is unknown."

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This medium tank has a powerful gun that features high damage per shot, good "
"depression, and high shell velocity, allowing the vehicle to turn the tide "
"of even the most desperate battle. Its good view range allows for spotting "
"opponents and securing the first hit. However, keep in mind that the armor "
"and mobility are rather mediocre."

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise_short"
msgstr "M4A1 Rev."

msgid "F73_M4A1_Revalorise_short_special"
msgstr "A good gun that causes high damage per shot"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 49"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_FL"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 49 FL"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_FL_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 49 FL"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_Liberte"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 49 Liberté"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_Liberte_descr"
msgstr ""
"A heavy tank that was originally known as Project 141. Since France needed "
"modern heavy tanks, development started immediately after World War II. "
"Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_Liberte_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This tank features reliable frontal armor that stands out from other French "
"vehicles. Make use of it when breaking through enemy lines or fighting in "
"close-range combat. Besides this, the tank has thick armor and a decent gun "
"with a high penetration rate and solid depression angles."

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_Liberte_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 49 L"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_Liberte_short_special"
msgstr "Good frontal armor and high penetration rate"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_descr"
msgstr ""
"A heavy tank that was originally known as Project 141. Since France needed "
"modern heavy tanks, development started immediately after World War II. "
"Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This tank features reliable frontal armor that stands out from other French "
"vehicles. Make use of it when breaking through enemy lines or fighting in "
"close-range combat. Besides this, the tank has thick armor and a decent gun "
"with a high penetration rate and solid depression angles."

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 49"

msgid "F74_AMX_M4_1949_short_special"
msgstr "Good frontal armor and high penetration rate"

msgid "F75_Char_de_25t"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 25 t AP"

msgid "F75_Char_de_25t_descr"
msgstr ""
"In 1950–1951, engineers of the FAMH company (Compagnie des forges et "
"aciéries de la marine et d'Homécourt) worked on the development of a medium "
"tank with a 90-mm gun and a rotating turret. Work was discontinued at the "
"preliminary design stage. Later, all elements of the vehicle were "
"incorporated in the Batignolles-Châtillon 25 t tank."

msgid "F75_Char_de_25t_short"
msgstr "B-C 25 t AP"

msgid "F77_FCM_2C"
msgstr "FCM 2C"

msgid "F77_FCM_2C_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development of the FCM 2C heavy breakthrough tank began at the end of 1916, "
"with the vehicle intended to replace the poorly designed Saint-Chamond and "
"Schneider CA1 assault tanks. An order was placed for a total of 700 vehicles "
"that were supposed to be produced in time for a new advance scheduled for "
"the spring of 1919. However, the order was canceled due to the end of the "
"war. As a result, the army received just 10 FCM 2C tanks from 1918 through "
"1922. Each vehicle had its own designation."

msgid "F77_FCM_2C_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A heavy French breakthrough tank project from 1918. In addition to its "
"impressive appearance, the FCM 2C boasts a decent 75 mm gun, as well as "
"moderate mobility for its incredible size and weight of 70 tons. Its large "
"pool of 600 HP is a nice addition that gives you the durability to outgun "
"most opponents in a range of confrontations."

msgid "F77_FCM_2C_short"
msgstr "FCM 2C"

msgid "F77_FCM_2C_short_special"
msgstr "Unique shape, increased HP"

msgid "F81_Char_de_65t"
msgstr "AMX 65 t"

msgid "F81_Char_de_65t_descr"
msgstr ""
"A heavy tank design was proposed by the AMX company in 1950. The vehicle was "
"developed alongside the AMX 50 100. It was supposed to feature reinforced "
"armor with a \"pike nose\" and sloped armor plates. The other components and "
"hull configuration resembled the Royal Tiger. Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F81_Char_de_65t_short"
msgstr "AMX 65 t"

msgid "F82_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Ter"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 54"

msgid "F82_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Ter_7x7"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 54 7x7"

msgid "F82_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Ter_7x7_descr"
msgstr ""
"A variant of the AMX M4 heavy tank based on the Project 141 with reinforced "
"front armor. It was planned to enhance the front armor by mounting a 280-mm "
"armor plate. Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F82_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Ter_7x7_short"
msgstr "AMX 54 7x7"

msgid "F82_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Ter_descr"
msgstr ""
"A variant of the AMX M4 heavy tank based on the Project 141 with reinforced "
"front armor. It was planned to enhance the front armor by mounting a 280-mm "
"armor plate. Existed only in blueprints."

msgid "F82_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Ter_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 54"

msgid "F83_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Bis"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 51"

msgid "F83_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Bis_FL"
msgstr "AMX M4 mle. 51 FL"

msgid "F83_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Bis_FL_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 51 FL"

msgid "F83_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Bis_descr"
msgstr ""
"The Project 141 was a variant of the AMX M4 heavy tank with reinforced front "
"armor. Development started in November 1949, but the vehicle was never "
"built. The project also included many calculations for different hulls on a "
"similar chassis."

msgid "F83_AMX_M4_Mle1949_Bis_short"
msgstr "AMX M4 51"

msgid "F84_Somua_SM"
msgstr "Somua SM"

msgid "F84_Somua_SM_descr"
msgstr ""
"A French heavy tank, presented as an alternative for the AMX 50 at a design "
"competition. Development started in 1946; however, the prototype was not "
"ready until October 1951. German tank-building technologies were applied in "
"the development of the vehicle: it was equipped with a 100-mm gun with a "
"magazine-system autoloader installed in an oscillating turret. The tank "
"underwent trials from January through July 1953, during which it did not "
"show any promising results. Consequently, the project was discontinued in "
"favor of the AMX 50."

msgid "F84_Somua_SM_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A heavy tank with a 5-shell magazine that can potentially deal 1,500 HP of "
"damage in a short time. Moreover, it features remarkable gun depression/"
"elevation angles and satisfactory mobility. The reliable frontal armor can "
"resist many shots, but the same cannot be said for the turret, where the "
"armor is weaker."

msgid "F84_Somua_SM_short"
msgstr "Somua SM"

msgid "F84_Somua_SM_short_special"
msgstr ""
"Excellent gun elevation/depression angles and magazine reloading system"

msgid "F85_M4A1_FL10"
msgstr "M4A1 FL 10"

msgid "F85_M4A1_FL10_descr"
msgstr ""
"Developed by Batignolles-Châtillon at the request of the Egyptian Armed "
"Forces, this tank represented a major modernization of the M4 Sherman. The "
"first vehicles manufactured featured the hull and chassis of the M4A1 and "
"the FL 10 turret of the AMX 13. However, the majority of vehicles used the "
"hull and the chassis of the M4A4. A total of 50 vehicles were manufactured "
"and saw service in the Egyptian Armed Forces until the mid-1960s. Later, the "
"remaining operational tanks were sent to the 20th Division of the Palestine "
"Liberation Organization in the Gaza Strip."

msgid "F85_M4A1_FL10_long_special"
msgstr ""
"A maneuverable vehicle with a rapid-firing gun. Its low damage per shot is "
"compensated by its high damage per minute. One of the distinctive features "
"of this vehicle is its high loading speed. However, this advantage is offset "
"by poor gun accuracy. In addition, its mediocre armor characteristics call "
"for cautious gameplay."

msgid "F85_M4A1_FL10_short"
msgstr "M4A1 FL 10"

msgid "F85_M4A1_FL10_short_special"
msgstr ""
"A gun with a magazine loading system and high damage per minute, high "
"mobility"

msgid "F87_Batignolles-Chatillon_12t"
msgstr "Bat.-Châtillon 12 t"

msgid "F87_Batignolles-Chatillon_12t_descr"
msgstr ""
"A light tank developed by Batignolles-Châtillon in the late 1940s. The "
"vehicle featured an oscillating turret and 75-mm gun. Never saw mass "
"production."

msgid "F87_Batignolles-Chatillon_12t_short"
msgstr "B-C 12 t"

msgid "F88_AMX_13_105"
msgstr "AMX 13 105"

msgid "F88_AMX_13_105_7x7"
msgstr "AMX 13 105 7v7"

msgid "F88_AMX_13_105_7x7_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 105 7"

msgid "F88_AMX_13_105_descr"
msgstr ""
"A variant of the AMX 13 developed in the late 1950s. The FL 12 turret "
"adjusted for a 105-mm gun was mounted on the vehicle. The new variant of the "
"AMX 13 did not see service in the French army, but was exported to other "
"countries; the vehicle was produced in Argentina under a license. Despite "
"the firepower was improved, the new design had several disadvantages. For "
"example, a greater recoil saw turrets crack sometimes."

msgid "F88_AMX_13_105_short"
msgstr "AMX 13 105"

msgid "F89_Canon_dassaut_de_105"
msgstr "AMX Canon d'assaut 105"

msgid "F89_Canon_dassaut_de_105_descr"
msgstr ""
"The Canon d'assaut de 105 tank destroyer is a combat vehicle design "
"developed by the AMX Company in 1958. According to archive records, this "
"tank destroyer was supposed to combine high maneuverability and mobility, "
"reliable armor (up to 100 mm in the frontal area), and a powerful 105-mm "
"gun. Later, the development was discontinued; no prototypes were built."

msgid "F89_Canon_dassaut_de_105_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This tank destroyer is the perfect choice for ambushes. Its excellent "
"mobility allows you to take an advantageous position on any map and make "
"full use of its accurate gun. This vehicle does not feature the best armor, "
"so it's a good idea to rely on concealment instead."

msgid "F89_Canon_dassaut_de_105_short"
msgstr "AMX Cda 105"

msgid "F89_Canon_dassaut_de_105_short_special"
msgstr "A great gun and impressive mobility"

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90"
msgstr "ELC EVEN 90"

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90_FL"
msgstr "ELC EVEN 90 FL"

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90_FL_short"
msgstr "ELC EVEN 90 FL"

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90_descr"
msgstr ""
"A series of vehicles developed by BRUNON-VALETTE under the ELC program in "
"the late 1950s. The goal was to create a light aeromobile tank for fire "
"support purposes. The vehicle had small dimensions and high maneuverability. "
"A total of 10 pilot vehicles with different types of armament were produced. "
"They underwent trials, but the vehicle never entered mass production."

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90_long_special"
msgstr ""
"An excellent recon vehicle with a low profile, exceptional mobility, and "
"great concealment. These features help to ensure it is always in the right "
"place at the right time. In addition, a three-shell autoloader gives "
"potential damage of 660 HP. However, don't forget its mediocre armor, which "
"is highly vulnerable to ramming."

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90_short"
msgstr "ELC EVEN 90"

msgid "F97_ELC_EVEN_90_short_special"
msgstr "A magazine reloading system and great mobility"

msgid "FCM_36Pak40"
msgstr "FCM 36 Pak 40"

msgid "FCM_36Pak40_descr"
msgstr ""
"In 1943, ten FCM 36 tanks captured by the Germans were converted into tank "
"destroyers. The vehicles fought in France with the Verstärkte Schnelle "
"Brigade West."

msgid "FCM_36Pak40_short"
msgstr "FCM36Pak40"

msgid "FCM_50t"
msgstr "FCM 50 t"

msgid "FCM_50t_descr"
msgstr ""
"Development was started in December 1945. The vehicle was conceived as an "
"alternative for the AMX 50t and combined archaic features typical of the pre-"
"war French tank-construction industry as well as German innovations. The "
"vehicle was to be equipped with an additional container trailer, equipment "
"for underwater driving, and a demountable mine clearer."

msgid "FCM_50t_long_special"
msgstr ""
"This heavy tank generally features the gameplay of a medium one: it's rather "
"fast, though large, and has a perfect gun and view range. On the other hand, "
"it does not have much armor, so it is more of a support vehicle than "
"anything else."

msgid "FCM_50t_short"
msgstr "FCM 50 t"

msgid "FCM_50t_short_special"
msgstr "A good gun, with perfect view range and preferential matchmaking"

